'''John Joseph Walsh Jr.''' (born 1937 in [[Mason City, Washington]]) is an American art historian, curator and museum director.  He served as director of the [[J. Paul Getty Museum]] from 1983–2000, supervising the planning and completion of the Getty's [[Richard Meier]]-designed [[Getty Center]] and transforming the Getty's art collection through new acquisitions.<ref>"Walsh, John [Joseph], Jr.." Dictionary of Art Historians (website). http://arthistorians.info/walshj</ref>

Walsh graduated from [[Yale University]] in 1961, where he was a member of [[Skull and Bones]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Father Escorts Virginia Galston At Her Marriage: Wheaton Alumna Wed to John J. Walsh Jr. in St. Ignatius' Here | work=[[New York Times]] | date=18 Feb 1962 | author=Bachrach, Bradford | pages=82}}</ref> Walsh earned a Ph.D from [[Columbia University]].  He worked in curatorial capacities at the [[Frick Collection]] and the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York and the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston|Museum of Fine Arts]], Boston, prior to assuming the directorship of the Getty.<ref>Getty Trust press release on the occasion of Walsh's retirement, Sept 2000 [http://www.getty.edu/news/press/leaders/walsh.html]</ref> Walsh is now on the Board of Trustees of the [[Hammer Museum]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/about/museum_board_and_staff.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503132938/http://hammer.ucla.edu/about/museum_board_and_staff.html |archivedate=2012-05-03 |df= }}</ref>

